<div class="bg-zinc-950 text-zinc-100">
  <.marketing_nav current={:docs} />

  <section class="py-16 sm:py-24">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 lg:px-8">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400">Use cases / Cassandra</p>
      <h1 class="mt-2 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-50 md:text-5xl">
        Letting an LLM run nodetool — safely
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-8 text-zinc-400">
        On a Cassandra cluster, "agent runs <code>nodetool repair</code>" is a coin-flip
        between "you reduced inconsistency by 0.001%" and "you took a replica offline for
        six hours". This page walks the boundary that makes the coin-flip a human's call.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">What the pack declares</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
        The shipping <code>cassandra</code>
        pack (see <.link
          navigate={~p"/packs/cassandra"}
          class="text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300"
        >the public pack page</.link>)
        publishes 45 nodetool + cqlsh actions across topology, health, schema, maintenance,
        repair, and node lifecycle. The risk-relevant ones for this incident:
      </p>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-zinc-300">
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">cassandra.nodetool_status</code>
          — risk <code class="text-emerald-300">low</code>, read-only. Cluster topology and per-node up/down state.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">cassandra.nodetool_tpstats</code>
          — risk <code class="text-emerald-300">low</code>, read-only. Thread-pool queue depth — the fastest signal for a saturated node.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">cassandra.nodetool_compactionstats</code>
          — risk <code class="text-emerald-300">low</code>, read-only. Pending and in-flight compactions per host.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">cassandra.nodetool_tablestats</code>
          — risk <code class="text-emerald-300">low</code>, read-only. Per-keyspace / per-table read counts, bytes, and latency.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">cassandra.nodetool_repair</code>
          — risk <code class="text-amber-300">high</code>. <code>keyspace</code>
          validated by
          pattern (<code>^[a-zA-Z][a-zA-Z0-9_]&#123;0,47&#125;$</code>); <code>mode</code>
          defaults
          to <code>preview</code>; 6-hour timeout. The default policy holds it for one approval.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Typical triage flow</h2>
      <ol class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-zinc-300 list-decimal pl-6">
        <li>Alert fires: read latency on <code>orders_ks</code> creeps up.</li>
        <li>
          Model runs <code>nodetool_status</code>, sees node 3 is DN (down), then
          <code>nodetool_compactionstats</code>
          on its peers — pending compactions piling up.
          All three are <code>low</code>, so they run unattended.
        </li>
        <li>
          Model proposes <code>nodetool_repair orders_ks</code>
          on the surviving replicas.
          The action is <code>high</code>, so the policy returns <code>require_approval</code>.
          The model surfaces the policy reason and its own one-line <code>reason</code>
          for the run.
        </li>
        <li>
          The approver gets an email and opens the run. They see the actor, the keyspace, the
          target runner, and the reason — then approve with one click. Because <code>mode</code>
          defaulted to <code>preview</code>, the approved run previews the repair unless the args
          explicitly asked for a full or incremental pass.
        </li>
        <li>
          Output streams into the run detail page, lands in the searchable cloud audit, and is
          recorded in the runner's hash-chained journal. If a repair exceeds its 6-hour timeout,
          the runner SIGTERMs the whole process group — the <code>nodetool</code> wrapper and
          anything it spawned — and escalates to SIGKILL after the 5-minute cancel grace.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">What the LLM cannot do</h2>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-zinc-300">
        <li>
          <strong class="text-zinc-100">Tear down a node on its own.</strong>
          <code>nodetool decommission</code>, <code>removenode</code>, <code>assassinate</code>, and
          <code>drain</code> <em>are</em>
          in the pack — and they all ship at <code class="text-rose-300">critical</code>, which the default policy <code>deny</code>s
          outright. No approval path; the runner never execs them. Lifting that is a deliberate
          policy edit, itself audited.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-zinc-100">Repair an arbitrary keyspace.</strong>
          A <code>keyspace</code>
          that fails the validation pattern is rejected before exec — the
          argument never reaches <code>nodetool</code>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-zinc-100">Talk its way past the gate.</strong>
          The runner advertises each action's risk from the trusted pack; the policy engine
          evaluates the authoritative value, not whatever the caller claims.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-zinc-100">Read secrets off the host.</strong>
          There's no <code>read_config</code>
          action, and any JMX or cqlsh output is run through
          redaction before it leaves the runner.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <%!-- FAQ --%>
      <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">
        Questions a Cassandra operator asks
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-6 divide-y divide-zinc-900 rounded-2xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60">
        <details class="group">
          <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-sm font-semibold text-zinc-100">
            Is repair really safe to hand to a model?
            <.icon name="hero-plus" class="h-5 w-5 text-zinc-500 transition group-open:hidden" />
            <.icon name="hero-minus" class="hidden h-5 w-5 text-indigo-400 group-open:block" />
          </summary>
          <p class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
            The model can <em>propose</em>
            a repair; a human decides. It ships at <code>high</code>,
            it defaults to <code>preview</code>, and the validated <code>keyspace</code>
            argument is
            the only thing it can vary. The destructive lifecycle commands sit a tier above, at <code>critical</code>, denied by default.
          </p>
        </details>
        <details class="group">
          <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-sm font-semibold text-zinc-100">
            How does emisar know an action is "high risk"?
            <.icon name="hero-plus" class="h-5 w-5 text-zinc-500 transition group-open:hidden" />
            <.icon name="hero-minus" class="hidden h-5 w-5 text-indigo-400 group-open:block" />
          </summary>
          <p class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
            The risk tier is declared in the action's YAML and travels with the pack's content hash.
            An operator trusts that hash once; the runner re-verifies it before every run. Change the
            risk in the YAML and the hash changes, which blocks dispatch until someone re-trusts it.
          </p>
        </details>
        <details class="group">
          <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-sm font-semibold text-zinc-100">
            Can I let routine repairs run without paging me every time?
            <.icon name="hero-plus" class="h-5 w-5 text-zinc-500 transition group-open:hidden" />
            <.icon name="hero-minus" class="hidden h-5 w-5 text-indigo-400 group-open:block" />
          </summary>
          <p class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
            Yes — approve once and issue a standing grant bounded by duration, runner, argument
            shape, and a use count. The next identical repair matches the grant and runs; anything
            outside it still stops for a human. Revoke the grant at any time.
          </p>
        </details>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-3 border-t border-zinc-900 pt-8 text-sm">
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/packs/cassandra"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-medium text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300"
        >
          Browse all 45 Cassandra actions <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3.5 w-3.5" />
        </.link>
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/security-model"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-medium text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300"
        >
          How the trust boundary works <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3.5 w-3.5" />
        </.link>
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/action-packs"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-medium text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300"
        >
          The action pack YAML reference <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3.5 w-3.5" />
        </.link>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <.marketing_footer />
</div>
